"""
mkt-context | judges | ch1–3 fill
present: ch1:v1,2,4,7,19,27,34; ch2:v1,8,10,16,23; ch3:v1,7,12,15,20,31 — 72 missing
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-1-3-fill.py

Context focus: tribal geography, ANE military practices, Deuteronomic cycle structure,
archaeological sites, Canaanite religion, charismatic judge pattern.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "1": {
    "3": "<p>The Judah-Simeon alliance reflects their geographic entanglement: Simeon's tribal allotment was entirely surrounded by (and eventually absorbed into) Judah's territory (Josh 19:1-9). The cooperative campaign 'each in his allotment' (<em>beḡôrālô</em>) was both a military necessity and a foreshadowing of Simeon's eventual loss of distinct tribal identity — Simeon disappears from the tribal lists in Deut 33 and vanishes as an independent entity in later history.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Bezek's location is debated — most commonly identified with Khirbet Ibziq in the hills of Ephraim, though a Judahite setting is expected from the narrative context. The battle against Adoni-bezek ('lord of Bezek') involves a Canaanite city-lord rather than a king of a named city-state, suggesting this was a localized chieftainship rather than a major urban center. The 10,000 dead signals a substantial coalition rather than a simple city-battle.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The mutilation of thumbs and great toes was a specifically disabling punishment for warriors: removing the thumb prevented sword and bow use; removing the great toes disrupted balance and made military movement impossible. The practice is attested in other ANE contexts as a way to humiliate defeated rulers while keeping them alive as a demonstration of power. Adoni-bezek's own admission that he had done this to 70 kings underscores the scope of Canaanite inter-city warfare in the pre-monarchic period.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The statement that Judah 'fought against Jerusalem and captured it, struck it with the sword, and set the city on fire' stands in tension with 1:21 (Benjamin did not drive out the Jebusites) and Josh 15:63 (same). The most common resolution: Judah's action was a raid or partial burning of the lower city without permanent garrisoning. Jerusalem/Jebus remained a Jebusite city-state until David's conquest (2 Sam 5:6-9) — its location on the tribal border between Judah and Benjamin left it in a perpetual no-man's-land of incomplete conquest.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The three geographic zones of Judah's territory — the <em>har</em> (hill country, the central ridge), the <em>negev</em> (the dry south), and the <em>Shephalah</em> (the western foothills) — represent a systematic sweep of Judah's entire allotment. Each zone had different Canaanite populations and different military challenges: the hill country was harder to approach but less fortified; the Negeb was Amalekite/Kenite territory; the Shephelah was where the great lowland Canaanite city-states were concentrated.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Hebron/Kiriath-arba ('city of Arba') was named for Arba the progenitor of the Anakim (Josh 15:13; 14:15) — the gigantic clan whose presence made the land terrifying to the pre-conquest spies (Num 13:28-33). The three Anakim sons Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai appear at Num 13:22 as the formidable occupants of Hebron. Caleb's earlier vow (Josh 14:12) to take this territory 'if YHWH is with me' is now being fulfilled in the tribal campaign.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Debir/Kiriath-sepher ('city of writing/books') has been tentatively identified with Khirbet Rabud in the Judean highlands, though Khirbet ed-Dhahiriyeh has also been proposed. The name suggests a scribal or administrative function — possible archive city — which would make it a significant administrative prize. The parallel account in Josh 15:15-19 adds that Debir was formerly called Kiriath-sannah (Josh 15:49), giving it a third name and underlining the difficulty of identifying these ancient sites with confidence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Caleb's offer of Achsah as a prize for the capture of Debir reflects the military marriage-alliance customs of the period — a daughter given to cement a relationship, in this case between Caleb's clan and a capable warrior. The parallel in Josh 15:16-17 confirms the tradition. Othniel's importance is signaled by his two appearances: here as Caleb's nephew and future son-in-law, and in ch3 as the first judge — the book is already constructing its first major character.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Othniel son of Kenaz is a Kenizzite — a non-Israelite group (cf. Gen 15:19) that had been absorbed into the tribe of Judah through Caleb's Kenizzite lineage (Num 32:12; Josh 14:6). His inclusion as the first judge and the paradigmatic deliverer of ch3 reflects the book's consistent interest in unexpected agents of salvation — foreign-stock individuals, left-handed men, women — through whom YHWH delivers Israel. The naming of Othniel here in ch1 prepares readers to recognize his return in ch3.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Achsah's initiative in approaching her father on her donkey to make a request is notable for its specificity: she 'dismounted from her donkey' before approaching, a gesture of respectful petition. The parallel in Josh 15:18 is nearly identical. Her request demonstrates independent agency within the social structures of the period — she negotiates her own inheritance supplement, and Caleb grants it without resistance. Ancient commentators treated her request as a model of bold but respectful petition to a beneficent father.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The 'upper springs and lower springs' (<em>gullot elyonot</em> and <em>gullot tahtiyyot</em>) of the Negeb were a vital resource in the semi-arid zone around Debir. Spring/cistern rights determined the viability of settlement in the arid south; granting springs with a land grant was the difference between a productive and a marginal inheritance. The topographic specificity of the request suggests authentic local memory preserved in the tradition.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Kenites — related to Moses' father-in-law (Hobab/Jethro, cf. Num 10:29-32; Judg 4:11) — settled among the Judahites in the Negeb near Arad. Their presence foreshadows Jael's role in ch4-5 (Jael was a Kenite woman). The Kenites were semi-nomadic metalworkers (the name may relate to <em>qayin</em>, smith) who maintained a special relationship with Israel throughout the early monarchic period; they appear again in 1 Sam 15:6 and the genealogical lists of 1 Chr 2:55.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Hormah (<em>ḥormāh</em>, from <em>ḥērem</em> — the ban/devotion to destruction) was so named because Judah and Simeon placed Zephath under the <em>ḥērem</em> — total destruction as a sacred act of war. The name recalls an earlier Hormah incident at Num 21:3 where Israel had vowed to destroy Canaanite cities if YHWH delivered them. The renaming of a city after the theological act performed there is a recurring practice in the conquest narratives (cf. Achor, 'trouble,' after Achan's sin in Josh 7).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Judah's capture of Gaza, Ashkelon, and Ekron — three of the five Philistine city-states — is textually contested: the Septuagint reads 'Judah did not take Gaza' (with a negation), which makes better sense of the consistent Philistine presence in subsequent Judges narratives. If the MT is correct that Judah took these cities, they were evidently not held permanently. The five Philistine cities (Gaza, Ashkelon, Ashdod, Ekron, Gath) formed a distinct political federation in the coastal plain throughout the Judges period.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Caleb's inheritance at Hebron is authorized by the Mosaic grant (cf. Deut 1:36; Josh 14:13-14) — his faithfulness during the spy mission earned him the specific territory the spies had reconnoitered. The expulsion of the 'three sons of Anak' (<em>yaldê hāʿănāq</em>) echoes the conquest of the Anakim by Joshua (Josh 11:21-22) but fills in the local Hebron detail. Caleb thus completes what Joshua had begun nationally at the local level.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The notice that Benjamin 'did not drive out the Jebusites who lived in Jerusalem' appears directly after v8's claim that Judah had fought and burned Jerusalem — a compositional juxtaposition that forces the reader to reckon with the incomplete character of the conquest. The Jebusites 'live with the people of Benjamin in Jerusalem to this day' (the narrator's perspective, pre-Davidic) — Jerusalem's Jebusite character persisted until 2 Sam 5:6-9, making it politically neutral territory available as David's capital for the united monarchy.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The House of Joseph's campaign against Bethel is narrated as a parallel to Joshua's Jericho operation: both involve a spy scene, a local informant who shows the entrance, and a promise of sparing the informant's household. Bethel ('house of God') was at this point still called Luz and was a major Canaanite city; it later became one of Israel's two royal sanctuaries (1 Kings 12:28-29). Its capture by the house of Joseph anticipates the city's later importance to the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The 'spies' (<em>meraggelîm</em>) sent to Bethel echo Joshua's spies to Jericho and Canaan (Josh 2:1; Num 13:2). The spy narrative structure — reconnaissance, encounter with a local, promise of protection in exchange for intelligence — is a recurrent biblical pattern of military cunning aligned with covenant faithfulness. The Luz/Bethel story preserves a tradition of the conquest that was distinct from Joshua's account and shows the house of Joseph acting with the same narrative tools as the earlier generation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The man who shows the spies 'the entrance to the city' is a structural parallel to Rahab (Josh 2) — a Canaanite insider who crosses to Israel's side in exchange for safety. Unlike Rahab, his motivation is not stated as faith or knowledge of YHWH's power; he acts under duress. His willingness to betray his city anticipates the theme of Canaanite informants that reappears in later Judges traditions (cf. the Kenite woman's betrayal in ch4).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The capturing and burning of Bethel/Luz follows the standard <em>ḥērem</em> pattern — the city is struck with the sword and burned — but the informant and his family are sent away 'to the land of the Hittites.' This preservation of life parallels Rahab's survival but with a different outcome: the man goes into exile rather than joining Israel. The phrase 'to the land of the Hittites' likely refers to the Neo-Hittite kingdoms of northern Syria (Carchemish, Hamath) that persisted into the Iron Age after the collapse of the Hittite Empire around 1200 BCE.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The new city built by the informant, which he also names Luz, is a striking act of cultural preservation under exile: he replicates his homeland in a foreign land, carrying the name with him. The 'land of the Hittites' where he settles (see v25) identifies his destination as the Neo-Hittite Syrian city-states. The vignette captures the fragmentation of Canaanite culture under Israelite pressure while acknowledging that conquest did not eliminate Canaanite cultural identity.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The shift from 'could not drive out' (vv1-26) to 'put to forced labor' (<em>mas</em>) when Israel grew strong is the key theological pivot of the tribal failures section. <em>Mas</em> (corvée, forced labor) violated the spirit of the <em>ḥērem</em> — instead of eliminating the Canaanites who posed a covenant danger, Israel exploited them economically. This same pattern anticipates Solomon's corvée system (1 Kings 5:13-14) and connects the Judges-era failures to the monarchic-era compromises. The Canaanites were not driven out but were turned into a permanent labor force within Israel's economy.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Ephraim's failure at Gezer is historically significant: Gezer was one of the major Canaanite city-states controlling the coastal plain and the road between the Shephelah and the highlands. It remained a Canaanite enclave throughout the monarchic period until the Egyptian pharaoh captured it and gave it to Solomon as a dowry when Solomon married Pharaoh's daughter (1 Kings 9:16-17) — a detail preserved in a diplomatic archive that confirms Gezer's longstanding Canaanite character well into the 10th century.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Zebulun's failure at Kitron and Nahalol follows the same pattern: 'did not drive out... but they lived among them and became subject to forced labor.' Nahalol is sometimes identified with Tell el-Beida or a site in the Jezreel Valley; Kitron is unknown. The detail that the Canaanites 'became subject to forced labor' rather than being driven out reflects the same compromise already noted in v28 — economic integration replacing covenantal separation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Asher's list of uncaptured cities is the most extensive of any tribe: Acco, Sidon, Ahlab, Achzib, Helbah, Aphik, and Rehob — seven cities, all in the coastal strip including the major Phoenician centers. Sidon was the pre-eminent Phoenician city of the early Iron Age (Tyre rose to prominence later). Asher's coastal territory was dominated by Phoenician culture, and the tribe's failure to displace these populations explains the persistent Phoenician cultural influence on Israel's northern coast throughout the Judges and monarchic periods.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'The Asherites lived among the Canaanites' — the formulation is reversed from the other tribes: not 'the Canaanites lived among them' (implying Canaanites as a minority within Israelite territory) but Asher living among the Canaanites (implying Asher as a minority within Canaanite coastal territory). This distinguishes Asher as the most thoroughly Canaanized tribe in the settlement — they assimilated into a Canaanite-dominant coastal culture rather than establishing Israelite dominance.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Naphtali's partial conquest in the Galilee region follows the same pattern: Beth-shemesh and Beth-anath remained Canaanite, and the Canaanites 'became subject to forced labor.' Beth-shemesh ('house of the sun') and Beth-anath ('house of Anath') are named for Canaanite deities — their survival as Canaanite cities within Naphtali's allotment meant the continued presence of Canaanite cultic centers inside Israel's tribal territory, a direct religious threat to covenant exclusivity.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The Amorites' confinement of Dan to the hill country prevented Dan from occupying its coastal-plain allotment, which included the Aijalon valley and the Shephelah approaches to Jerusalem. The Amorites 'persisted in dwelling in Mount Heres, in Aijalon, and in Shaalbim' — these sites are in the foothills west of Benjamin, the area where the Philistines would later dominate. Dan's failure to secure its territory is the direct background for the tribal migration narrated in ch18, when Dan relocates entirely to the far north.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Amorite boundary 'from the ascent of Akrabbim, from Sela, and upward' defines the Transjordanian Amorite territory on the southeastern frontier. This geographic notation closes the tribal failures section by noting that the Amorites maintained a continuous territorial presence through both the east and west banks of the Jordan. The framing of the chapter with an initial question about tribal leadership (v1) and a closing picture of widespread incomplete conquest establishes the central tension that the book of Judges will develop: YHWH gave the land, but Israel failed to take it fully.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "2": "<p>The Angel's covenant indictment recites the specific obligations that Israel violated: 'make no covenant with the inhabitants of this land; tear down their altars.' These are the two key prohibitions of Exod 23:32-33; 34:12-16 and Deut 7:2-5. The breach was not ignorance but deliberate non-compliance with known covenant terms — making the judgment that follows covenantally inevitable rather than arbitrary.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The consequence YHWH announces — the remaining nations will be 'thorns in your sides' and 'their gods will be a snare to you' — is the negative fulfillment of the covenant warning in Exod 23:33; Num 33:55; Deut 7:16. The 'snare' (<em>pah</em>) metaphor is particularly apt: a trap is not immediately lethal but catches the unwary and holds them; the Canaanite gods would not immediately destroy Israel but would entangle Israel in progressive apostasy.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people's weeping at Bochim upon hearing the Angel's words is the immediate, temporary response of covenant grief — the same pattern as Israel's weeping at Sinai after the golden calf incident. The narrator will note in vv11-19 that this remorse was not durable; the cycle of apostasy would begin again after Joshua's generation died. The weeping at Bochim is genuine grief, but grief without sustained structural change — a recurring diagnosis throughout Judges.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The place is named Bochim (<em>bōkîm</em>, 'weeping ones') after the event — an etiological naming in which a geographic site memorializes a spiritual moment. The practice of sacrificing at this site 'to YHWH' after the judgment-oracle is the appropriate covenantal response, but the sacrifice itself follows the weeping rather than preceding it, suggesting reparative rather than preventive worship. Bochim's location is uncertain; Josephus identified it with Bethel (Ant. 5.98), which would link it to the Bethel sanctuary of later Judges narratives.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The flashback to Joshua's dismissal of the people (parallel to Josh 24:28) repositions the reader chronologically: ch2:6 overlaps with Josh 24:28-31 to re-establish the timeline before narrating the post-Joshua degeneration. This literary technique — beginning a new section by backing up to a prior moment and running forward from it — is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic compositional method, which frames each historical period with a death of the previous leader and a transition to the new era.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The continuity of covenant fidelity is tied to living memory: 'the people served YHWH all the days of Joshua, and all the days of the elders who outlived Joshua, who had seen all the great work that YHWH had done for Israel.' When personal witnesses to the Exodus and conquest died, their testimony died with them. The problem the verse diagnoses is structural — Israel had not yet developed the liturgical and catechetical institutions needed to transmit covenant memory across generations without direct witnesses (cf. Deut 6:20-25 as the intended answer to this problem).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Joshua's burial at Timnath-heres ('portion of the sun') in the hill country of Ephraim — note the contrast with Josh 24:30 which names it Timnath-serah ('portion of abundance'). The two names may reflect different traditions or a deliberate reversal in one text. The burial site within his inheritance underscores the connection between Joshua and his tribal allotment — a leader who received the land he had fought for, dying in it and buried in it, which stands in contrast to Moses who was denied entry.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The programmatic verdict 'the people of Israel did what was evil in the sight of YHWH' (<em>wayyaʿăśû bĕnê yiśrāʾēl ʾet-hāraʿ bĕʿênê Yhwh</em>) is the Deuteronomistic History's standard evaluative formula, used throughout Judges and Kings to mark each cycle of apostasy. The phrase functions as a theological summary that simultaneously reports behavior and pronounces judgment from YHWH's perspective. Its repetition throughout Judges creates a rhythmic structure of failure against which the occasional deliverances stand out.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Forsaking YHWH 'the God of their fathers who had brought them out of Egypt' and serving the Baals (<em>habbĕʿālîm</em>) is the specific covenantal violation that triggers judgment. Baal (lord, owner) was the Canaanite storm deity associated with rainfall, fertility, and agricultural productivity — his worship was the perennial temptation in an agricultural society dependent on seasonal rain. The plural 'Baals' refers to the local manifestations of the storm deity worshipped at different hilltop shrines (<em>bāmôt</em>) throughout Canaan.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The pairing of Baal and Ashtaroth (<em>hāʿaštārôt</em>) represents the male and female divine pair of Canaanite religion — Baal the storm god and Astarte the goddess of love, war, and fertility. Ugaritic literature (discovered at Ras Shamra from 1929 onward) has provided extensive documentation of this divine pantheon. The plural 'Ashtaroth' (like 'Baals') indicates local goddess-shrines rather than a single entity. The prophets' consistent condemnation of Baal-Asherah/Astarte worship reflects the specific religious danger the Judges-era narrative is diagnosing at its root.</p>",
    "14": "<p>YHWH 'sold them into the hand of their enemies' (<em>wayyimkōr ʾōtām bĕyad ʾôyĕbêhem</em>) — the 'selling' (<em>makar</em>) language frames the covenant punishment as a commercial transaction: Israel has effectively been sold into slavery to foreign powers, the same condition from which YHWH had redeemed them from Egypt. The theological irony is pointed: by abandoning YHWH for Baals they return to the bondage-condition that defined their pre-YHWH existence. The plundering of Israel by enemies is the external expression of the internal disintegration caused by covenant betrayal.</p>",
    "15": "<p>YHWH's hand against Israel 'as YHWH had sworn' (<em>kaʾăšer nidbber Yhwh</em>) links the judgment explicitly to the covenant curses of Leviticus 26 and Deuteronomy 28 — the judgment is not arbitrary anger but the execution of previously announced covenant consequences. The phrase 'they were in terrible distress' (<em>wayyēṣer lāhem mĕʾōd</em>) is the narrative signal that Israel has reached the nadir of the cycle, the moment of maximum pressure that precedes the cry for deliverance and the raising of a judge.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'They did not listen to their judges, for they whored after other gods and bowed down to them' — the verb 'whored' (<em>zānâ</em> after) is the prophetic metaphor for covenant infidelity as marital betrayal. YHWH's relationship with Israel is figured as a marriage (cf. Hos 2:13-14; Jer 3:1-5; Ezek 16); idolatry is therefore adultery against the divine husband. The Judges narrator employs this metaphor structurally: the judges are not failed because YHWH's deliverance was insufficient but because Israel did not sustain covenant fidelity even during periods of successful leadership.</p>",
    "18": "<p>YHWH's compassion (<em>niḥam</em>, 'was moved to pity/relented') in response to Israel's groaning under oppression is the pivot of each judge cycle. The theological logic: even covenant-breaking Israel, when in sufficient suffering, elicits divine pity because of the covenant relationship — YHWH remembers not Israel's faithfulness (which has lapsed) but his own commitment to them. The empathy expressed — 'YHWH was moved to pity by their groaning because of those who afflicted and oppressed them' — characterizes YHWH as a deity who responds to suffering even in disobedient covenant partners.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'But whenever the judge died, they turned back and were more corrupt than their fathers' — the progressive deterioration motif. Each generation's apostasy is worse than the previous: 'they did not drop any of their practices or their stubborn ways.' The Judges narrative has a downward trajectory throughout — the later judges (Jephthah, Samson) are morally more compromised than the earlier ones (Othniel, Gideon), reflecting the progressive corruption that v19 predicts. The book charts not just repeated cycles but a spiral of deepening covenant failure.</p>",
    "20": "<p>YHWH's anger and the covenant indictment — 'this people have transgressed my covenant that I commanded their fathers' — frames the theological diagnosis of the entire Judges period. The covenant is treated as a corporate, trans-generational obligation: the 'fathers' here are the Sinai generation; their descendants' apostasy violates a covenant they individually never ratified but are held responsible for as members of the covenant community. This collective covenant theology is the basis for prophetic calls to return to the ancestral covenant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>YHWH's decision not to drive out the remaining nations reverses the conquest promise — the blessing becomes withheld because the condition of faithfulness has not been met. This is a striking instance of conditional covenant logic: YHWH had promised to drive out the nations before Israel (Josh 3:10), but the condition was Israel's obedience. When the condition failed, the promise was suspended, and the remaining nations became instruments of discipline rather than targets of elimination.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The testing rationale — 'to test Israel, whether they will take care to walk in the way of YHWH as their fathers did' — gives a positive theological framing to what might appear as divine abandonment. The remaining Canaanites function as a proving ground: their presence is not YHWH's failure to complete the conquest but a deliberate educational instrument. This testing language connects to the Deuteronomic concept of the wilderness wandering as a test (Deut 8:2-3: 'he humbled you and tested you') — Israel's entire history is figured as a covenant examination.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "2": "<p>The 'teaching war' rationale for leaving nations in the land — 'so that the generations of the people of Israel might know war, to teach war to those who had not known it before' — is a second, complementary justification alongside the testing rationale of v4. The concern is practical: a generation born in the land, without experience of the conquest campaigns, needed military formation. This dual rationale (testing covenant fidelity + military training) reflects the Deuteronomistic framing of Israel's history as a period of both moral and martial preparation for the monarchy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The list of remaining nations — the five Philistine lords, all Canaanites, Sidonians, and Hivites on Mount Lebanon to Lebo-hamath — represents a geographic sweep from the coastal plain (Philistines) to the Phoenician coast (Sidonians) to the northern Lebanese Beqa' valley (Hivites/Hamath). The 'five lords of the Philistines' (<em>sĕranê pĕlištîm</em>) is a specific political title — the Philistine pentapolis was governed by city-lords rather than kings, a political structure distinctive to Philistine governance, possibly related to their Aegean origins.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The testing rationale is made explicit: 'to test Israel by them, whether Israel would obey the commandments of YHWH, which he commanded their fathers by Moses.' The phrase 'by Moses' (<em>bĕyad mōšê</em>, literally 'by the hand of Moses') anchors the test in the specific covenant mediation of Sinai — it is not an abstract moral examination but a test against the specific commands delivered through a known covenant mediator. This frames the Judges period as a Mosaic-covenant examination period whose results will determine the shape of Israel's subsequent history.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Israel's dwelling 'among the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Amorites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites' — the six-nation list — recapitulates the conquest target list of Deut 7:1 and Josh 3:10. The list functions as a literary marker: by naming all six nations as Israel's neighbors rather than defeated enemies, the text signals complete covenantal failure in the settlement project. The people YHWH had commanded to destroy or displace are now the people among whom Israel lives on equal terms.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Intermarriage with the Canaanites and their gods is the ultimate stage of assimilation that Deut 7:3-4 had specifically forbidden: 'you shall not intermarry with them... for they would turn away your sons from following me.' The verse confirms that Israel had crossed every boundary — territorial separation, cultic separation, and now familial separation — creating the conditions for the complete religious syncretism that the prophets will later condemn. The worship of Canaanite gods that follows in vv7ff. is the inevitable downstream effect of the intermarriage the law had prohibited.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Cushan-rishathaim of Aram-naharaim is the first of the oppressing foreign powers. His name meaning 'doubly wicked Cushite' (<em>rišātayim</em> = double wickedness) is almost certainly a polemical epithet substituted for his real name by the Israelite tradition. Aram-naharaim ('Aram of the two rivers') is the upper Mesopotamian region known as Paddan-aram in the patriarchal narratives — the homeland of Rebekah and Leah and Rachel. The eight-year servitude (<em>šmōneh šānîm</em>) is the first of the stylized numbers that structure the Judges cycles.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Othniel is 'raised up' (<em>wayyāqem</em>) by YHWH as a deliverer — the same Hiphil of <em>qum</em> used for YHWH's acts of raising prophets and kings throughout the Deuteronomistic History. His identity as 'Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb's younger brother' connects his emergence to the conquest hero already introduced in ch1 — the judges are not random charismatic figures but emerge from the families and clan-networks already established as faithful in the settlement narratives. The cry of Israel (<em>zāʿaq</em>) is the covenant signal: suffering people appealing to their covenant God.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Spirit of YHWH (<em>rûaḥ Yhwh</em>) coming upon Othniel is the charismatic anointing that defines the judges as a category distinct from kings or priests: their authority is not hereditary, institutional, or geographical but immediate and pneumatic. The same Spirit pattern governs Gideon (6:34), Jephthah (11:29), and Samson (13:25; 14:6, 19; 15:14). The Spirit empowers him to 'judge Israel' and then 'go out to war' — the judicial and military functions are combined in the judge's role, distinguishing Israelite governance in this period from both the elder-council model and the later monarchic model.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The forty-year rest period is a stylized round number representing one full generation. 'The land had rest forty years' (<em>watiššqōṭ hāʾāreṣ ʾarbaʿîm šānâ</em>) — the subject is the land rather than the people, reflecting a concept of the land itself experiencing peace or disturbance in resonance with its inhabitants' covenant status (cf. Lev 26:34-35, where the land 'enjoys its sabbaths' during exile). The rest period ends with Othniel's death, not with renewed apostasy directly — the cycle is reset when the charismatic leader dies and his institutionalizing effect on the community dissolves.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Eglon's coalition with Ammon and Amalek creates a Transjordanian alliance that takes 'the city of palms' (Jericho, cf. Deut 34:3). Jericho's capture by Moab is particularly resonant: the first city taken by Israel in the conquest is now retaken by a foreign power, reversing the conquest and symbolically returning Israel to pre-conquest vulnerability. Ammon and Amalek were traditional enemies of Israel in the Transjordan and Sinai respectively; their combination with Moab represents a comprehensive eastern and southern threat.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Eighteen years of servitude to Eglon is one of the shorter oppression periods in Judges (cf. eight years under Cushan, forty years under Philistines in 13:1). The varying lengths of the oppression periods — 8, 18, 20, 7, 40, 18, 40 years — are stylized but not uniform, suggesting the tradition preserved memory of different degrees of severity. Moab's oppression is centered on the Benjamin-Jericho area (the 'city of palms') rather than extending across all Israel, which explains why Ehud, a Benjaminite, is the deliverer.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Ehud's dagger was 'a cubit long' (<em>gōmed</em> — a unit of about 12 inches, possibly a short forearm-length) and double-edged. Its concealment on his right thigh — where a left-handed man's sword hand would not naturally reach — was the tactical advantage that made the assassination possible: Eglon's guards would check the left hip for a right-hander's sword and find nothing. The detail reflects an ancient awareness of the security advantage of left-handedness as a form of asymmetry that exploits standard security assumptions.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The narrator's note that Eglon was 'a very fat man' (<em>ʾîš bārîʾ mĕʾōd</em>) is one of the Bible's most vivid physical descriptions of an antagonist. The fatness serves several narrative functions: it explains why the dagger disappears completely in v22 (the fat closes over the blade), it may symbolize the prosperity of an oppressor living off Israel's tribute, and it creates dark comedy appropriate to this trickster narrative. Ancient Hebrew narrative rarely comments on physical appearance without narrative purpose; here the detail is load-bearing for the plot.</p>",
    "18": "<p>When Ehud had finished presenting the tribute, he sent away the people who had carried it — leaving himself alone with Eglon. The staging is deliberate: Ehud creates the private access he needs for assassination by using the tribute ceremony's natural endpoint as an opportunity to disperse witnesses. The public tribute presentation gave him legitimate access to the king's presence; the dismissal of the bearers removed the witnesses.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Ehud 'turned back from the idols at Gilgal' — he had apparently departed with the bearers toward Gilgal but returned, claiming to have a secret message. The 'carved images' (<em>pĕsîlîm</em>) near Gilgal may have been standing stones associated with the Gilgal sanctuary (cf. Josh 4:20). His invocation of a divine message — 'I have a word of God for you' (<em>dĕbar ʾĕlōhîm lî ʾēlêkā</em>) — causes Eglon to command silence, clear the room, and stand up in anticipation of divine speech. The irony: the 'word of God' will be delivered through iron rather than voice.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Ehud 'reached with his left hand and took the sword from his right thigh and thrust it into his belly.' The narrative reversal is complete: the tribute-bearer becomes the executioner; the sword concealed in the wrong place (right thigh for a left-hander) is drawn at the critical moment; the king who commands Israelite tribute receives Israelite steel. The scene is deliberately ironic throughout — the assassin acts as if he is a messenger from the divine king while serving the human king who oppresses YHWH's people.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'The handle also went in after the blade, and the fat closed over the blade, for he did not pull the sword out of his belly; and the dung came out.' This is the Bible's most graphically detailed assassination scene, with a dark scatological humor characteristic of some Israelite trickster narratives (cf. the Elijah-Baal contest mockery in 1 Kings 18:27). The fat closing over the blade explains the disappeared weapon; the 'dung' signals that the belly-thrust had perforated the intestines. The graphic detail serves to deflate Eglon's royal dignity and affirm his death beyond doubt.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Ehud escapes through the 'porch' (<em>misdĕrônâ</em>) — a hapax legomenon of uncertain meaning, possibly a vestibule, portico, or private passage in the upper chamber architecture. The exact escape route is unclear, which has generated extensive ancient and modern discussion. What is clear is that Ehud exited the locked inner room before the servants discovered Eglon's body — the architectural detail is preserved because it explained how Ehud vanished despite the locked doors that confused the servants.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The servants' assumption that Eglon was 'relieving himself' (<em>mēsîk raglāyw</em>, literally 'covering his feet') — a euphemism for defecation in a private chamber — is the pivot of the black comedy. The locked doors signaled privacy; privacy in an inner chamber after a meal was reasonably interpreted as bathroom use. Their restraint in waiting — 'they waited until they were embarrassed' — gives Ehud precisely the time he needs to escape. The servants' embarrassment (<em>bōšû</em>) at interrupting their king has fatal political consequences.</p>",
    "25": "<p>When the servants finally take a key (<em>hammapteaḥ</em> — perhaps the only occurrence of 'key' in this sense in Biblical Hebrew) and open the doors, they find their king 'fallen dead on the floor' — the word <em>nāp̄al</em> (fallen) is used throughout Judges for those slain in battle, giving the discovery scene a battlefield vocabulary. The discovery ends the black comedy and pivots to Ehud's military campaign — the assassination was the precondition for the military deliverance, not an end in itself.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ehud escaped to Seirah while the servants delayed — his escape was directly enabled by the confusion and delay in the palace. Seirah's location is unknown but appears to be in the Ephraim hill country based on the narrative sequence (v27 mentions Ephraim). The geography of Ehud's operation spans the Jericho plain (Eglon's palace), the Gilgal region (the idol-stones), and the Ephraim highlands (Seirah) — Ehud moved through Moabite-controlled territory using the legitimate cover of a tribute mission.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The trumpet blast (<em>yiqqāʿ bašōpār</em>) in the Ephraim hill country is the standard military signal for mustering troops (cf. Num 10:9; Josh 6:4-5; Judg 6:34). Ehud's trumpet transforms his personal act of assassination into a national moment of military opportunity — the Moabites at the fords are now leaderless and their retreat route is about to be cut. The combination of assassination + swift troop mobilization + seizure of crossing points is a sophisticated operational plan, not merely opportunistic fighting.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Seize the fords of the Jordan against the Moabites and let no one pass' — the tactical key. The Jordan fords were the only practical crossing points; controlling them trapped the Moabite force west of the Jordan without a retreat route. The same tactical logic appears in Gideon's operation (7:24-25) and throughout the conquest and Judges period. The command 'the LORD has given your enemies the Moabites into your hand' is the standard holy-war declaration that signals YHWH's involvement in the battle and authorizes Israelite aggression.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The killing of approximately 10,000 Moabites — described as 'all strong, able-bodied men; not a man escaped' — is presented as a comprehensive military victory. The emphasis on the completeness of the slaughter ('not a man escaped') echoes the <em>ḥērem</em> language of total-war ideology. The Moabite force trapped between Ehud's pursuers and the sealed Jordan fords was annihilated rather than driven back — a military operation that removed Moab's military capacity rather than merely their occupation force.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'So Moab was subdued that day under the hand of Israel, and the land had rest for eighty years' — the eighty years (double the normal forty) is the longest peace period in Judges, suggesting either that Ehud's deliverance was particularly thorough or that the tradition preserved a memory of an unusually long period of stability. The completion formula 'the land had rest' (<em>watiššqōṭ hāʾāreṣ</em>) closes the Ehud cycle with the same phrase as the Othniel cycle (v11), confirming that the second judge's deliverance met the same covenantal standard as the paradigmatic first judge's.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(existing, JUDGES)
    save_comm('context', 'judges', existing)
    print('Judges 1-3 context fill: 72 verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
